  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model to calculate the intrinsic value of Motorola Solutions (MSI). This estimates the value of the company based on its future free cash flows discounted back to their present value.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>We begin with MSI's most recent trailing 12-month free cash flow. FCF represents the actual cash a company generates after accounting for cash outflows to support operations and maintain its capital assets.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We project the free cash flow to grow over the next 5 years based on its historical CAGR and operational performance, capping our estimate to be reasonably conservative.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume a perpetual growth rate of 3%, representing a stable, mature growth phase in line with long-term macroeconomic GDP growth rates.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>The projected cash flows and terminal value are discounted back to today's value using a mathematically derived discount rate, establishing a baseline of return for the risk taken.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value is adjusted by net cash (cash and equivalents minus total debt) to arrive at the Equity Value. We divide this by the outstanding diluted shares to find the intrinsic value per share.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

